    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when you approve the work. Common Gaggenau repairs: oven door hinge assembly $385-$580 (most common BO 480 / BX 480 steam-oven service item); steam-oven descaling service $245-$385 (the calcium-scale recovery cycle, not a part replacement); steam generator boiler element $580-$880; oven control board $485-$780; oven temperature sensor $245-$385; convection fan motor $325-$485; dishwasher door spring assembly $345-$525 (the 2017-2021 DF cohort pattern); dishwasher drain pump $285-$425; dishwasher control board $445-$680; cooktop induction generator $580-$880 per zone; cooktop glass surface $880-$1,400 (premium component); ventilation blower motor $385-$580; wine climate sensor $285-$425. Gaggenau pricing runs at the top of the luxury repair tier — parts ship from Germany via BSH USA's Irvine, CA distribution (typical 5-10 day lead on less common items, common wear parts on the truck for the dominant BO / DF / VG model families)."
  },
  {
    q: "My Gaggenau steam oven has calcium buildup — is that a repair?",
    a: "Usually it's a descaling service, not a component repair — and it's one of the most common Gaggenau service calls in LA because our local water hardness drives the build-up faster than the manual implies. Symptoms: steam-oven cycles getting longer, water reservoir filling more often than usual, sometimes a descale prompt on the front panel that's been ignored. The fix on most BO 480 / BX 480 / BS 484 units is a full descale cycle using the manufacturer-approved descaler — typically 90 minutes on-site, $245-$385 total. We use OEM Gaggenau descaling agent (third-party citric-acid substitutes can damage the boiler over time). If the unit hasn't been descaled in 18+ months and the boiler element is showing reduced output even after descale, the element itself may need replacement ($580-$880) — but we always run the descale cycle first to isolate the issue before quoting boiler parts. On LA hard-water service routes (Beverly Hills, West Hollywood, San Gabriel Valley), we recommend a 6-month descale interval rather than the manual's 12-month default."
  },
  {
    q: "Do Gaggenau and Bosch share parts?",
    a: "Some parts, yes — and it matters for service economics and parts lead time. Gaggenau, Bosch, Siemens, and Neff are all owned by BSH Hausgeräte GmbH (Bosch-Siemens joint venture, 100% owned by Robert Bosch GmbH since 2015). Across the BSH portfolio, certain components are shared at the engineering level — drain pumps, fan motors, some sensors, certain control board chassis. On a Gaggenau dishwasher's drain pump or a Bosch Benchmark dishwasher's drain pump, the OEM is sometimes the same supplier with cosmetic differences. Practical service implication: when a part needs to come from Germany via BSH USA's Irvine, CA distribution, we sometimes have access to faster channels through Bosch / Thermador stocking when the part number cross-references. Where the brands diverge is the high-end Gaggenau-specific assemblies — the BO 480 / BX 480 steam oven boilers, the Vario cooktop modular system, the specific cabinetry-flush mounting hardware on the fully-integrated DF dishwashers — those are Gaggenau-only and ship on Gaggenau's own lead-time schedule."
  },
  {
    q: "How long do Gaggenau appliances last?",
    a: "Built for 20-plus year service life if you maintain them, and Gaggenau's German engineering bears that out in the field. The cabinetry-grade construction, the steel-spec door hinges, the panel electronics, the cookware-grade surface materials — these are engineered for the kitchen renovation cycle outlasting the appliance, not the other way around. Where Gaggenau differs from Liebherr or Miele in longevity: the steam systems (boilers, descale paths, valve assemblies on BO / BX series) need active maintenance — a descale schedule that the homeowner actually follows, not just when the prompt appears on screen. Properly maintained, a Gaggenau BO 480 will run 20+ years. Neglected on descaling, the boiler element fails at year 8-10 and the repair gets expensive. The dishwashers, cooktops, and ventilation hardware are lower-maintenance and reliably run through year 15-18. We tell you the maintenance cadence at every service visit so you're not surprised at year 8."
  },
  {
    q: "Is it worth repairing a Gaggenau oven?",
    a: "Almost always, and the math is straightforward. A single Gaggenau wall oven retails $8,000 to $15,000 in the US — the BO 480 combi-steam oven is in the $11,000-$14,000 range, the BS 484 full-steam variant is $9,000-$11,000, the BX 480 vacuum-seal-capable steam unit pushes $15,000+. Against those replacement-unit costs, a $600 hinge repair or a $850 boiler element swap or a $780 control board replacement is a comparatively small expenditure to recover 5-10 more years of service life. The repair-vs-replace math tips toward replacement only in a few specific situations: structural cabinet damage from a kitchen fire or flood, control-board failure on a model whose board is no longer manufactured (rare on Gaggenau — BSH maintains parts inventory for 10+ years on most lines), or owner preference to update kitchen aesthetic during a remodel. Outside those scenarios, the answer on Gaggenau is generally repair. We tell you the math at diagnostic before any parts get ordered."
  },
  {
    q: "Where can I find the official Gaggenau manual or warranty information?",
    a: `Our technicians work independently of Gaggenau's factory service network — we're often faster and available same-day in Southern California.`
  }
